@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "About | Clint McMahon";
    ViewData["Description"] = "Software engineer and architect in Minneapolis. 20+ years building systems for legal, healthcare, and government.";
}

<!--
==========================================================================
ABOUT PAGE — WRITING PROMPTS
==========================================================================
This page has five sections. Each section has a comment block below that
explains what to write, why it matters, and questions to work through.
Replace the [FILL IN] placeholder text with your own words, then delete
the comment block above each section.

What makes a personal About page work:
- Specific details beat vague claims. "Wells Fargo" > "a Fortune 500 bank."
- One short real story reveals more character than three paragraphs of credentials.
- Mention something you do outside of work. It signals you're a person, not a job title.
- Don't summarize your resume. The portfolio page does that.
- Write the way you'd describe yourself to someone at a conference, not in a cover letter.
==========================================================================
-->

<div class="page-intro is-centered">
    <h1>About</h1>

    <!--
    SECTION: SUBTITLE (one line under the heading)
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    What it is: A single sentence that frames who you are and what
    the reader will find on this page. NOT a job title.

    Questions to work through:
    - If someone asked "so what's your deal?" at a conference, how
      would you answer in one sentence?
    - What's the thing about you that surprises people?

    Examples of what works:
    - "How I got into software, what I've learned, and what I'm
       building when I'm not on client work."
    - "Software engineer in Minneapolis. I also make espresso and
       build things no one asked for."

    Examples of what doesn't work:
    - "Experienced professional with a passion for technology." (too generic)
    - "Full-stack developer specializing in enterprise solutions." (sounds like a LinkedIn summary)
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    -->
    <p>[FILL IN: Your one-liner — see prompt above]</p>
</div>

<div class="page-body is-centered">

    <!--
    SECTION 1: ORIGIN STORY
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    What it is: How you got into programming. The shorter and more
    specific the better. This is not your career timeline — it's the
    detail that makes you real to a reader.

    Questions to work through:
    - What was the very first program you remember writing or hacking on?
    - How old were you when you first got paid to write code?
    - What was the thing that made you think "I could actually do this"?
    - Was there anything unconventional about how you got started?

    Keep it to 2–3 sentences. Name actual things: languages, companies,
    people, ages. Those specifics are what readers remember.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    -->
    <p>[FILL IN: How you got into programming — see prompt above]</p>

    <!--
    SECTION 2: WHAT YOU DO NOW
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    What it is: What your work actually looks like today. Not a list
    of skills — a description of the problems you solve and who you
    solve them for.

    Questions to work through:
    - Who do you work with? (industry, size of company, type of role)
    - What is the thing clients call you for specifically?
    - What's a one-sentence description of a recent project you can
      talk about publicly?
    - Where are you based, and does that matter to your work?

    Tip: Lead with the client's problem, not your technology stack.
    "I help law firms modernize legacy systems" lands better than
    "I work in .NET and Azure." The tech can follow.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    -->
    <p>[FILL IN: What your work looks like today — see prompt above]</p>

    <!--
    SECTION 3: THE HUMAN MOMENT (optional but worth it)
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    What it is: One short story that reveals something about how you
    think or what you've learned. A mistake, a lesson, a thing that
    changed how you work. This is the section that makes people trust you.

    Questions to work through:
    - What's a mistake you made early in your career that you still
      think about?
    - Is there a moment where something went badly and you learned
      something from it?
    - What's something you'd tell a 22-year-old version of yourself?

    This should be 3–5 sentences. Name the situation specifically —
    "I destroyed a production database" > "I made a serious mistake."
    The lesson should follow naturally from the story. Don't editorialize
    it heavily — let the story do the work.

    If you can't think of one, skip this section entirely rather than
    writing something generic about "always learning."
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    -->
    <p>[FILL IN: Your human moment / lesson — see prompt above, or delete this paragraph]</p>

    <!--
    SECTION 4: OUTSIDE OF WORK
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    What it is: 2–3 things you do outside of client work. This is where
    readers decide whether they want to actually meet you.

    Questions to work through:
    - What's a side project you've shipped, even if it's small?
    - What do you do on Saturday mornings?
    - What are you currently learning that has nothing to do with work?
    - Is there something you're into that would surprise people?

    Be specific. "I make espresso" is fine. "I pull shots on a [machine]
    and I'm currently dialing in a [bean]" is better. Specificity signals
    you actually do this thing, rather than listing it as a personality trait.

    One or two sentences max on the side project(s). Keep it human.
    ----------------------------------------------------------------
    -->
    <p>[FILL IN: Side projects and personal interests — see prompt above]</p>

    <!--
    CALL TO ACTION — keep this, just update the phrasing if you want
    -->
    <p>
        The <a href="/blog">blog</a> has what I'm thinking about, the <a href="/portfolio">portfolio</a> has what I've built, and the <a href="/contact">contact page</a> is there if you want to talk.
    </p>

</div>
